Sometimes you just gotta not care 😎 

Also - if you are thinking about recording your process, and feel awkward doing so - here are a few tips
When I started recording myself at the gym back during Covid - I felt very much uncomfortable at first cause - well people.

I do think it’s easier to go about it if you treat it like a job. Pretend you’re getting paid for it. You need to do it - so let the people around you feel uncomfortable that they are spending their time judging you 😄
Don’t forget to smile at haters

And if anyone is concerned that they will be “caught” in your video - tell them they are the last person you want in your camera roll 🤣🤣🤣

Good luck! 👍🏼

The moment I tell people that I used to be 36 pounds overweight, I instantly get recognition for my current physique

The moment, when I bring up that I did not grow up in America and English is not my first language, I instantly get credit for how I sound and come off 

The moment I tell people of my educational background, and the fact that I’ve paid off all of my student loans - I instantly get a reaction of how impressive it is and how I should be proud of it

The moral of the story is, if you don’t speak of your achievements, many will assume that there are none. I used to think that speaking abbot what you have done for yourself is going to be overlooked, but not at all. You’re not bragging, you’re just proudly announcing your hard work and dedication. 
And how would anyone know if they weren’t with you through that part of your life?

Moment of vulnerability here 
they say we are most authentic in our vulnerable state, and this is mine. At my heaviest I was 156 pounds, with little to no muscle, mass, and a very unhealthy relationship with food. 
at my core, I was happy with how I looked, and I do not think that I recognized any issues with myself. 
I liked me for me. I like the way I looked. I was genuinely happy. 
Looking back, I’m proud of the fact that I have decided to make myself a priority, and change my body to be who I am today 
it wasn’t easy, nor was it fast. But it was worth it.

1 session difference 

Leg Alignment Gains 

@sonyabil did the smart thing and came to me for some mild stiffness but mostly maintenance work. After assessing her gait, I saw her left foot is stuck in supination during  stance phase of gait. 

Look at what happens to the knee and even the hip when she takes a step. Since the foot is locked up, the hip also locks up, and the knee compensates taking the impact of the ground force tension. 

If @sonyabil never came to me, this would of never been addressed.  She would of kept going with her life and eventually developed a knee issue. The issue  would get worse so now she seeks my help because she is in pain. At this point, it’s late. Knee is already damaged and my job gets harder. I would like to work smarter not harder and the smart thing to do is to come to me early 

Be proactive not reactive. Be like @sonyabil

So here are my suggestions for anyone starting 
—————————————————————
1.Goals are great - treat them as a map - you might not hit all of the destinations at once at least you have it payed down
2. Keep comparing yourself to yourself only!! Dont be tempted to look at me for example 🫣 I didn’t start yesterday - I’m still learning and figuring my body out too….
3. Record yourself! I don’t care if you’re not feeling like it - bloated? That’s ok!! Hair not washed? It’s all good! Just get into a habit of recording yourself every week and keep going back to that first video for inspiration!

Finding self-worth is a deeply personal and individual journey. It requires self-reflection, introspection, and a willingness to embrace your uniqueness and strengths. Here’s an example of steps you can take to find your self-worth: 

1️⃣ Practice Self-Compassion: Treat yourself with the same kindness and understanding that you would offer to a close friend. Recognize that everyone makes mistakes and experiences setbacks, and that these do not define your worth as a person.

2️⃣ Identify Your Strengths: Make a list of your skills, talents, and qualities that you value. Consider what others have complimented you on and what you enjoy doing. This can be anything from problem-solving abilities to creativity or being a good listener.

3️⃣ Practice Self-Care: Take care of your physical, emotional, and mental well-being. Engage in activities that bring you joy and help reduce stress. Prioritize your needs without feeling guilty about it.

#selflove #selfcare #youareworthit

Let’s say you’ve been feeling stressed and overwhelmed lately due to a busy work schedule and personal commitments. It’s essential to take some time to focus on your own needs and recharge. Here’s a step-by-step example of how you can prioritize yourself:

1️⃣ Self-Reflection: Take a moment to reflect on how you’ve been feeling and identify the areas of your life that are causing the most stress. This might include work-related tasks, personal relationships, or other responsibilities.

2️⃣ Identify Your Priorities: Determine what aspects of your life are most important to you. Is it your health, family, career, personal growth, or something else? Recognize that it’s okay to prioritize yourself and your well-being. 

3️⃣ Set Boundaries: Learn to say no when you feel overwhelmed or stretched too thin. Setting boundaries with work, family, and friends is crucial to avoid burnout.

Working out your upper body is important for various reasons. 

1. Posture improvement: Regularly working out your upper body can strengthen the muscles in your back, shoulders, and core. This helps you maintain better posture, preventing the rounding of shoulders and reducing the strain on your neck and upper back.

2. Increased stability: A strong upper body contributes to overall stability and balance. Strengthening your arms, chest, and back muscles helps in daily activities like carrying heavy groceries or maintaining balance while performing other physical tasks.

3. Enhanced functionality: Building upper body strength can improve your ability to perform daily tasks effortlessly. From lifting objects overhead to pushing or pulling heavy doors, having a strong upper body makes these movements easier and reduces the risk of injury.

4. Bone health: Resistance exercises involving the upper body, such as weightlifting or push-ups, stimulate bone growth, increasing bone density. This becomes particularly crucial as we age, helping prevent conditions like osteoporosis.

5. Mental well-being: Physical exercise has been proven to boost endorphin levels, leading to improved mood and reduced stress. Engaging in upper body workouts can be both physically and mentally satisfying, giving you a sense of accomplishment and promoting relaxation.
